{[%evp 0,10,25,20,26,12,12,21,29,-4,9,14,33] Welcome to this course. I present
you a complete repertoire on the Nimzo Indian Defence for Black. In my opinion,
this course is my best work till date for Modern Chess. I have offered novel/
unknown suggestions against all major setups. Our surprises start as early on
as the fourth move! Most of the analysis in this repertoire was prepared for a
Candidate, showcasing the quality of the analysis of the repertoire.} 1. d4 Nf6
2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 {The starting point of this course.} 4. Qc2 {One of the
major moves in the position. This is covered in the first chapter.} (4. f3 $5 {
The sharpest system against the Nimzo. White prepares to build a massive
center with e4. Here, I recommend the extremely rare} Ba5 {which has been
played in only 11 games till date! Black retains flexibility between ...c5 & ..
.d5. Black has had tremendous success here, boasting a score of a massive 68.
2%.} 5. e4 {If they play e4, we'll play ...d5.} (5. a3 {can be met with} c5 6.
d5 b5 $132 {This is basically 4.f3 c5 5.d5 b5 variation with a3-Ba5 included.
The inclusion of a3 & ...Ba5 favours Black.}) 5... d5 6. e5 Nfd7 7. f4 c5 $132
{the lines go on but Black is able to obtain a rich position everywhere. Our
point is that when compared to the 4.f3 d5 5.a3 Be7 variation, the bishop on
a5 is better placed on a5 than it would have been on e7.}) (4. a3 {Another
aggressive system. White forces us to give up the bishop.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {
[%csl Rc3,Rc4][%cal Gf2f3,Ge2e4] They accept a spoilt pawn structure in hopes
of building a massive center with f3 & e4. Black typically plays ...b6-Ba6-Nc6
in some order here. Instead of that, I recommend the rare} Ne4 6. Qc2 f5 {
avoiding all f3 ideas. We want to play ...b6-Ba6 next. If they play f3, we'll
play ...Nd6 and attack their c4-pawn. This leads to a more strategic battle
where's usual attacking plans don't work out for them.}) ({The fourth chapter
focuses on the} 4. Bd2 O-O 5. e3 {variation. Here, I recommend a somewhat rare}
({sidelines like} 5. Nf3) ({or} 5. a3 {are covered in the eight chapter.}) 5...
c5 {instead of the usual ...d5 line. The critical position arises after} 6. a3
Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8. Ne2 b6 9. d5 Ba6 {after which White has a couple of
choices to choose from : 10.b3 or 10.Qd3. The nature of the position remains
dynamic, yet Black retains objective balance everywhere. In most of the lines,
the positions get wild where all three results are up for grabs.}) (4. e3 {
The most widely played move in the position. This is covered in the fifth
chapter. Here, instead of the usual moves, I recommend the rare} Nc6 {[%cal
Ge6e5] preparing to meet Bd3 with ...e5. Black wants to create an imbalance
right off the bat! White has three major choices here.} 5. Bd3 {The most
played move. However, this is the move we were hoping to be played out. Here,
I recommend sharpening up the position with} ({the natural} 5. Nf3 {can be met
with} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d6 $13 {[%csl Gc1,Rc3,Rc4,Gf1][%cal Ge6e5] Black prepares .
..e5. We'll have the thematic 2 bishop vs spoiled pawn structure battle.}) ({
the logical} 5. Nge2 {is met with} e5 6. d5 Ne7 $132 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gd7d6,Gc7c6]
Black will soon undermine the center with ...c6, leading to a long strategic
battle.}) 5... e5 $1 $13 {leading to a complex strategic battle.}) (4. g3 {
Against the 'Catalan-Nimzo' hybrid, I recommend a few 'standard moves'. Don't
worry the core idea is still quite fresh.} O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. Nf3 dxc4 7. O-O Nc6
{and here, White has a few options to choose from.} 8. Qa4 {Dubov's speciality.
White wants to play Qb5. Here, I recommend playing} ({the most played} 8. a3
Be7 9. e4 a6 $15 {[%cal Gb7b5] usually offers Black an objective advantage.
More details in the 7th chapter.}) ({Against the natural} 8. Re1 {I recommend
the rare} h6 $5 {avoiding Bg5 ideas. Black will play ...Rb8 with the idea of
expansion on the Queenside with ...b5 next. This is quite rare, but
Nepomniachtchi played an instructive model game to beat the Indian prodigy
Raunak Sadhwani here.}) 8... Nd5 9. Qc2 Be7 {and after} 10. Rd1 {my
recommendation is the novel} a5 $5 {gaining space on the Queenside. Black
often claims an objective edge here. More details in the seventh chapter.}) ({
sidelines like} 4. Qb3) ({and} 4. Qa4) ({and} 4. Bg5 {are covered in the 8th
chapter.}) {here, I recommend the rare} 4... h6 $5 {which was employed by
Gukesh to win an important game against Abasov in the Candidates 2024. Here,
White has two major approaches : 5.a3 or 5.e4.} 5. e4 {the most ambitious move
in the position. Here, we employ} (5. a3 {against this, I recommend} Bxc3+ 6.
Qxc3 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Rd7d6,Rb8d7,Re6e5,Yd7d5,Yc7c5] preparing ...Bb7. We may
then play ...d6-e5 or ...d5-c5. Unlike the usual lines, White doesn't have the
option of playing Bg5 here.}) 5... c5 $5 {leading to an extremely sharp and
strategically complicated position on the board. This has been played in only
13 games so far which showcases the rarity of the variations. Good luck
fighting out here!} *

