{[%evp 0,28,20,20,18,28,28,28,20,-5,23,2,33,33,63,9,44,16,30,26,45,37,26,26,25,
24,16,18,28,8,8] In the first chapter, we'll cover the 4.Qc2 variation of the
Nimzo Indian.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White develops their
knight and prepares to expand with e4.} Bb4 {[%cal Gb4c3] The Nimzo-Indian
Defence. Black brings their bishop out to stop White's expansion plans with e4.
We also threaten to spoil their pawn structure with ...Bxc3.} 4. Qc2 {[%cal
Ge2e4,Ra2a3] Perhaps the most widely played move at the club level. White
brings their queen out to defend the knight on c3. Typically, White continues
by playing a3 or e4 on the next move. White players want to be solid if they
play this line.} h6 $5 {[%cal Gh6g5,Rf6h7,Re2e4,Re4e5] this rare move is my
suggestion. This caught my attention after Gukesh's famous win over Abasov in
the Candidates 2024. Black avoids Bg5 ideas and vacates the h7-square for
their knight against a future e4-e5 expansion.} 5. e4 {The most ambitious move.
White gains space in the center.} ({There are plenty of other logical moves
for White. Let's discuss them individually.} 5. Nf3 {against this, I recommend
undermining the center with} c5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc5d4]} (5... O-O {be careful
to not castle early with ...h6 included. You might run into} 6. g4 $16 {
[%cal Gg4g5,Gh1g1]}) 6. dxc5 $5 (6. e3 {this is generally too passive.} cxd4 7.
exd4 O-O {[%csl Rc4,Rd4][%cal Gd7d5] Black will play ...d5 next and hopes to
create an isolani in the center.} 8. Bd3 (8. a3 {also makes sense.} Bxc3+ 9.
Qxc3 b6 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4][%cal Rc8c4,Rd7d5,Rc8a6,Ra8c8,Rc8c3] since the e & c
pawns are traded, Black has a better chance to attack the c4-pawn.} 10. Be2 d5
$1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd5c4]} 11. b3 Nc6 12. O-O Ba6 $132 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4][%cal
Ga8c8] White's central pawns are under pressure.}) 8... d5 {if they allow us
to play ...dxc4, we'll be strategically better.} 9. c5 $5 {the thematic
expansion. If White manages to play a3-b4 next, they'll be better.} b6 {
we start undermining!} 10. a3 Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 bxc5 12. dxc5 a5 {an important
move. We cannot allow them to play b4 freely!} 13. O-O (13. b4 axb4 14. axb4 d4
$1 {this is a critical intermezzo!} 15. Qb2 (15. Nxd4 $4 Nd5 16. Qb2 Nxb4 $19 {
[%cal Ga8a1,Rb4d3]}) 15... Rxa1 16. Qxa1 Bb7 $132 {[%csl Rf3,Rg2][%cal Gb7f3,
Gd4d3,Rd3e2] Black keeps great counterplay here.}) 13... Ba6 {we don't offer
them the time to play b4 now.} 14. Bf4 (14. Bxa6 Ne4 $1 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Rc3a1]
} 15. Qc2 Nxa6 $11 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ga6c5]}) 14... Bxd3 15. Qxd3 a4 $11 {
[%csl Rb2,Rc5,Gd5,Ge6][%cal Gb8c6] Black keeps more fluidity in the center. If
they manage to develop comfortably, It is Black who would be looking to apply
pressure here.}) 6... Na6 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ga6c5] looking to recapture with
the knight.} (6... Bxc5 {is a bit premature. After} 7. Bf4 $14 {[%cal Ge1c1,
Re2e4,Rc3b5] White keeps a small edge.}) 7. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Re1g1]} ({asking
to give up the bishop with} 7. a3 {also makes a great deal of sense. Here, I
recommend} Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 Nxc5 {[%csl Rf1] looking for quick play. White is
slightly lagging behind in development.} 9. g3 b6 10. Bg2 Bb7 11. b4 $5 (11.
O-O O-O {[%cal Ga8c8,Gd7d5] they have nothing better than playing b4 here.})
11... Nce4 12. Qd4 d5 13. cxd5 Qxd5 $11 {[%csl Rb4,Rc3,Ge4][%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c1,
Gh8d8,Gd8d1,Ra7a5] the c3-square is weak. Black will play ...0-0 & ...a5 next.
Our lead in development compensates for the bishop pair. ½-½ (32) Xiong,J 
(2647)-Yoo,C (2600) Chess.com INT 2024}) 7... Nxc5 8. Bg2 Nce4 $1 {looking to
spoil their pawn structure.} 9. O-O Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bc5 {[%cal Gd7d6] If White
doesn't act quickly, Black will develop comfortably.} 11. e4 $5 {here, it is
important to know the following motif.} Nh7 (11... O-O 12. e5 Nh7 13. Nd4 $16)
12. e5 Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] preparing ...b6-Bb7.} 13. Nd2 b6 14. Ne4 Bb7
$132 {the more the pieces get trade, the eaiser it will be for Black to play
against White's pawn structure. Black wants to play ...Bxe4 next. An
instructive game here is 0-1 (57) Abasov,N (2632)-Gukesh,D (2743) Toronto 2024}
) (5. a3 {asking us to give up our bishop. This is quite thematic in the Qc2
variation of the Nimzo.} Bxc3+ 6. Qxc3 b6 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Gh6g5] compared to
the usual lines, Black has an added advantage of not allowing Bg5 here.} 7. Nf3
(7. f3 {[%cal Ge2e4]} d5 8. e3 Ba6 $132) (7. Qg3 {This is an additional option
available for White since they haven't played e3 or Nf3.} Nc6 $1 {an important
move to remember.} (7... O-O $4 8. Bxh6 $18) 8. Nf3 (8. Qxg7 $6 Rg8 9. Qxh6
Nxd4 $15 {[%csl Rc1,Gd4,Rf1,Gf6,Rg1,Gg8][%cal Gd4f5,Gc8b7,Rd4c2] look at the
lead in development!}) (8. d5 Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5]} 9. e4 $5 {a very ambitious
way of playing.} (9. Qxg7 Ng6 $19 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh8h7]}) 9... O-O 10. Bd3 (
10. e5 Ne4 11. Qe3 exd5 12. cxd5 Nc5 $132 {[%csl Rd5,Re5] White's pawns in the
center are a bit vulnerable.}) 10... Ng6 11. Ne2 exd5 {we need to strike back
in the center quickly or else they'll consolidate their advantage after
finishing development.} 12. cxd5 Re8 13. Nc3 Nh5 14. Qf3 Ne5 15. Qd1 Nxd3+ 16.
Qxd3 Qh4 17. O-O d6 $11 {[%cal Gf7f5,Re8e5,Re8f8,Yc3b5,Yc8a6] Black will
release the tension in the center with ...f5 & ...Rf8/Re5. The position
remains balanced.}) 8... Rg8 $5 {[%csl Rg3] White's queen doesn't have access
to good squares anymore.} 9. d5 (9. e3 Ne4 10. Qh3 Qf6 $132 {[%csl Rh3][%cal
Gg7g5,Gd7d5,Gc8b7,Ge8c8]}) (9. Qh4 Bb7 10. e3 g5 11. Qxh6 Qe7 $17 {[%csl Rh6]
[%cal Ge8c8]}) 9... Ne7 10. dxe6 dxe6 $11 {[%cal Ge7f5,Gc8b7]}) 7... Bb7 {
here, they can choose between the e3 or g3 setup.} 8. e3 (8. g3 {the more
positionally sound setup.} O-O 9. Bg2 d6 10. O-O Nbd7 {[%cal Ra7a6,Rb6b5,Gc7c5]
Black can either play ...a6-b5 (typically played when they play b4) or ...
c5-d5 next.} 11. b4 (11. b3 Rc8 12. Bb2 c5 13. Rfd1 d5 {[%csl Rc3] While White
enjoys the advantage of the bishop pair, we apply more pressure in the center.}
14. dxc5 (14. Rac1 {here,we should liquidate.} cxd4 15. Qxd4 dxc4 16. Rxc4 Rxc4
17. Qxc4 Bd5 $132 {[%csl Rb3,Gd5,Rg2][%cal Gd8a8,Gf8c8,Gd5g2]}) 14... bxc5 15.
cxd5 exd5 {[%csl Rb3,Gc5,Gd5][%cal Gd8b6] this would have been a great
position for white if they had their a3 pawn on a2 but with the b3-pawn weak,
Black retains counterplay.}) 11... a6 $5 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gb6b5]} 12. Bb2 (12.
a4 c5 $132 {[%csl Rb4,Rd4]}) 12... b5 $1 13. c5 Bd5 {[%csl Gd5] our bishop is
now established in the center. We'll play for light-square control here.} 14.
Nd2 (14. Ne1 a5 $11 {[%csl Ra3,Rb4][%cal Ga5b4,Gf6d5]}) 14... Bxg2 15. Kxg2 Nd5
16. Qb3 f5 $132 {[%csl Gd5,Ge6,Gf5][%cal Re2e4,Rf5e4]}) 8... O-O 9. Be2 d5 (
9... d6 $5 {this is more fighting. Here's a sample line.} 10. O-O Nbd7 11. b4
Ne4 12. Qc2 c5 13. Bb2 f5 14. Ne1 Qg5 $132 {the computer evaluates this as
slightly better for white but in a practical game, I think the chances are
even.}) 10. b3 Nbd7 11. O-O c5 12. Bb2 Ne4 13. Qd3 Rc8 $132 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4]
with pressure down the central pawns.}) (5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 (6. Bd3 c5 {typical
undermining operation in the center.} 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 cxd4 9. exd4 d5 10.
c5 {the only way to avoid Isolani.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4,Re1][%cal Ge6e5,Gf8e8,Ge8e1]
} 11. Ne2 a5 12. O-O b6 $11 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Gc8a6] we undermine their center
without allowing b4.}) 6... d5 {[%cal Gc7c5] next up, ...c5.} (6... c5 7. dxc5
Na6 8. Be2 {is an improvised version for White.}) 7. Bd2 (7. Bd3 c5 $11 {
[%csl Rc4,Rd4][%cal Gc5d4,Gd5c4]}) (7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 b6 9. b3 Bb7 10. Be2 {
transposes.}) 7... c5 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6,
Ga8c8,Gc8c1,Gf6e4] the pressure exerted with ...Ne4 or ...Nc6 allows us to
equalise comfortably.}) (5. Bd2 c5 {usual undermining operation.} 6. a3 Bxc3 7.
Bxc3 cxd4 8. Bxd4 Nc6 9. Bc3 O-O 10. e3 d5 $11 {[%csl Rf1,Rg1][%cal Gf6e4]})
5... c5 $5 {This is the whole point behind ...h6. White cannot keep their
center.} 6. d5 {the most popular move.} (6. e5 {is weaker.} cxd4 7. a3 Bf8 $3 {
[%cal Gf8g7,Re5f6,Rf6g7] this move changes the outcome of the variation!} 8.
Nge2 (8. Nb5 a6 9. Nxd4 Qa5+ $17) 8... dxc3 9. exf6 Qxf6 10. Nxc3 Nc6 $15 {
[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] with a stable extra pawn for Black.}) (6. Nf3 d6 {[%cal
Gd6e5]} 7. Be2 cxd4 8. Nxd4 O-O 9. O-O e5 $11 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb4c3] White
cannot maintain their pawn structure.}) (6. dxc5 {the most critical response.}
Bxc5 7. e5 $5 {the critical test.} (7. Nf3 d6 {[%csl Gc5,Rd4][%cal Gb8c6,Ge8g8]
Black has a great version of the Maroczy as their bishop is out.} 8. Be2 Nc6 9.
O-O O-O $11 {[%csl Gc5,Gc6,Rd4][%cal Ge6e5,Ga7a6,Rc8g4,Rc6d4]}) (7. Be2 d6 8.
Nf3 {transposes.}) 7... Ng4 8. Ne4 Qb6 9. Nxc5 Qxc5 10. f4 d6 {White needs to
play some strange moves here.} 11. Qe2 $5 (11. Bd3 dxe5 12. Qe2 $5 f5 (12... e4
$5 {also merits attention.}) 13. h3 e4 14. Bxe4 fxe4 15. hxg4 e5 $13 {[%cal
Gc8d7,Gd7c6,Ge8g8] with a wild position OTB.}) (11. exd6 {the natural
recapture is weak. After} Nc6 12. Nf3 O-O $15 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ge6e5,Gc5d6]
Black is better.}) 11... h5 $1 12. Nf3 (12. exd6 Nc6 13. Nf3 b6 $11 {[%csl Rc1,
Rf1]}) 12... Nd7 13. exd6 Qxd6 $11) (6. a3 {allows us to spoil their pawn
structure.} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. Ne2 O-O (9... e5 10. h3) 10. O-O b6
11. f4 cxd4 12. cxd4 Ba6 $132 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc6a5,Ga8c8,Gc8c4] a great
position to play for a dynamic game!}) 6... exd5 7. exd5 (7. cxd5 Qe7 {allows
Black to get rid off one of their central pawns.} 8. Bd2 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Nxd5 10.
Bxg7 Rg8 11. Qe2 Rxg7 12. exd5 d6 $11 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f6] with a
comfortable equality.}) 7... b5 $5 {going for the kill!} 8. cxb5 (8. Be3 O-O
$15) (8. Qe2+ $5 Qe7 9. Qxe7+ Kxe7 10. cxb5 (10. d6+ Kxd6 11. Bf4+ Kc6 12.
cxb5+ Kb7 13. Nge2 a6 $11 {[%cal Gd7d5] Our king can no longer be attacked.})
10... d6 11. Bd2 Nbd7 12. O-O-O Nb6 $11 {[%csl Gc5,Rd5,Gd6][%cal Gb6d5,Rb4c3]
with the usual pressure against the pawn on d5.}) 8... O-O 9. Bd3 (9. Bc4 a6
10. Nge2 axb5 11. Bxb5 {transposes.}) 9... a6 {we start underming their
queenside.} 10. Nge2 (10. bxa6 $6 {loses a move unneccesarily.}) 10... axb5 11.
Bxb5 Nxd5 12. O-O Nf6 {[%cal Gd7d5] Black will play ...d5 next.} ({another
option is} 12... Bxc3 13. Nxc3 Nb4 14. Qd1 d5 15. a3 d4 $5 {1-0 (59) Sadhwani,
R (2659)-Maghsoodloo,P (2719) London 2024}) 13. a3 (13. Rd1 Ba6 {we are always
happy to swap the light-squared bishops in this line.} 14. Bxa6 Nxa6 15. Ne4
Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Nc7 $11) 13... Bxc3 14. Nxc3 (14. Qxc3 Qb6 $132 {[%cal Gc8a6,
Gb8a6,Gd7d5]}) 14... d5 $132 {White retains the advantage of bishop pair while
Black keeps the center. The position is dynamically balanced.} *

