{[%evp 0,32,20,16,28,28,28,20,28,-19,14,18,31,37,37,36,21,12,19,19,19,39,57,57,
52,60,67,59,38,50,106,55,91,0,0] In the second chapter, we'll cover the
dynamic 4.f3!? variation in the Nimzo.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {
The sharpest line in the Nimzo complex. White prepares e4. Here, I recommend a
move which has only been played in 11 games out of the 20100 odd games in the
line.} Ba5 $5 {an extremely deep move. Black retains flexibility between ...d5/
...c5 setups. We'll choose our setup based on White's response.} (4... c5 {
here, White doesn't play 5.a3 but instead, they expand with} 5. d5 $5 {[%csl
Rb4] keeping our bishop on b4 misplaced. Black doesn't have the option of
playing ...b5-b4 or ...Ba5-Bb6 here.}) (4... d5 {against this, they play} 5. a3
{[%csl Rb4][%cal Ge2e4] and kick our bishop. ...Ba5 no longer works because of
b4-c5. White will be able to play e4 next.}) 5. e4 {the critical test.} (5. a3
c5 {Black's point. The bishop is better placed on a5 than it was on b4!} 6. d5
{the critical test.} (6. dxc5 {is practically weaker. After} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Na6
{White's pawn structure is terrible.} 8. Qd4 b6 9. cxb6 d6 $1 10. bxa7 Nc5 11.
Rb1 e5 12. Qd2 O-O 13. e4 Rxa7 14. Ne2 Nh5 $132 {[%cal Gh5f4,Ge2g3,Rd8h4,Rf7f5]
Black is down a couple of pawns but keeps much better pieces & pawn structure.
We'll play ...Qh4 or ...f5 next.}) 6... d6 7. e4 O-O 8. Bd3 {the most logical
move.} (8. Nge2 $5 {can be met with the thematic} exd5 9. cxd5 b5 $1 {[%csl
Gb5,Gc5,Gd6] Black starts play down the Queenside!} 10. Ng3 c4 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4]
[%cal Ga7a6,Ga5b6,Gb8d7]} 11. Be3 {[%cal Ge3b6]} (11. Be2 Qb6 $15 {[%csl Re1]})
11... Nbd7 12. Be2 a6 13. O-O Bb6 {eliminating the bad-bishop.} 14. Qd2 Bxe3+
15. Qxe3 Nc5 $11 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ga6a5,Gb5b4] without the dark-squared bishops,
Black's pieces are not cramped. We'll play ...Re8 followed by ...a5-b4 in the
future. Whenever possible, try to dominate the dark-squares in the position.})
8... exd5 9. cxd5 Nh5 {[%cal Gf7f5] going for a quick ...f5.} 10. Nge2 (10. Be3
$2 f5 11. Nge2 f4 $17 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7e5]}) 10... f5 11. exf5 Bxc3+ {spoiling
their structure.} 12. bxc3 (12. Nxc3 Qh4+ $15 {[%csl Re1] Black's point.})
12... c4 $1 {[%cal Gd8h4,Gh4c4]} 13. Bb1 Bxf5 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd8b6] with a
comfortable position. White's structure is ruined.}) (5. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2b4]
This was played by Dennis Lazavik once. White threatens b4 without playing a3.}
Nc6 $5 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc6b4,Gd7d5] preventing b4. Black threatens ...d5.} (
5... c5 6. dxc5 $5 Na6 7. Bd2 $14 {[%cal Rb2b4] this is the point behind
White's play.}) 6. a3 {White threatens b4.} (6. e4 {allows us to challenge
their center with} d5 7. e5 Nd7 {here, the critical line goes with} 8. cxd5
exd5 9. f4 {White consolidates their center. We should strike back with} Ndxe5
$1 10. dxe5 d4 11. b4 Bxb4 12. Rxb4 Nxb4 13. Ne4 Qd5 $13 {leading to an
imbalanced game.}) 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 b6 {[%cal Gd7d6,Gc6a5,Gc8a6] Black is
going to play against the weak c4-pawns.} 8. e4 d6 9. Bd3 Na5 10. Nh3 Qe7 $132
{[%cal Gc8b7,Gf6d7,Ge8c8,Rf7f5] Black will play ...Nd7-Bb7/Ba6 & ...0-0-0 next.
}) 5... d5 {we challenge their center.} 6. e5 {the critical test.} (6. Qa4+ {
also makes sense.} Nc6 {[%csl Rd4] the d4-pawn remains vulnerable.} 7. cxd5
exd5 8. Bb5 {here, I recommend to release the tension with} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 dxe4
10. fxe4 O-O {[%csl Rc3,Rd4,Re1,Re4] White has problems with their center and
king.} 11. Bg5 (11. e5 $6 Ne4 $15 {[%cal Ge4c3,Rd8h4]}) 11... Bd7 12. Qd1 (12.
e5 {doesn't win material. After} a6 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Qc2 Qd5 $15 {[%csl Rg5]
[%cal Gd5g5] Black dominates the light-squares.}) 12... Re8 13. Ne2 h6 14. Bxf6
Qxf6 $11 {[%csl Re4,Rg2][%cal Gf6g5,Ga8d8] White's pawn structure is weak.}) (
6. cxd5 exd5 7. e5 Nfd7 8. f4 c5 {transposes.}) 6... Nfd7 {the bishop on a5 is
more useful than the bishop on e7.} 7. f4 (7. cxd5 exd5 {transposes.}) 7... c5
{Black strikes the center. They can either release the tension, or keep it.} 8.
cxd5 (8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Be3 {maintaining the tension in the center. Here, we
recommend} (9. cxd5 exd5 {transposes.}) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 Ne7 $5 {[%cal Ge8g8,
Rd5c4,Ga5c3] Black will play on the light-squares.} 11. Be2 dxc4 12. O-O (12.
Bxc4 Nb6 $11 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ga5c3,Gb6d5]}) 12... Bxc3 13. bxc3 Nb6 $11 {
[%cal Gc8d7,Gb6d5] Black will play on the light-squares.}) 8... exd5 9. Nf3 Nc6
10. Be3 {White's main move. They want to guard the d4-pawn.} (10. Bb5 {here, I
recommend releasing the tension with} cxd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 O-O 13. Bd2 {
We need to get our c8-bishop into the game.} (13. Qxd5 Qb6 $44 {[%csl Re1]
[%cal Gf8d8] their king is stuck in the center.}) 13... a6 14. Be2 (14. Bxd7
Bb6 $15 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gb6g1] White has issues with their king.}) 14... Nb8 {
[%cal Gb8c6] rerouting the knight to a better square.} 15. Qxd5 Nc6 16. Qxd8
Rxd8 17. Be3 Be6 $11 {[%cal Gc6d4] we'll play ...Nd4 next.}) {here, we should
release the tension in the center with} 10... cxd4 11. Nxd4 O-O {[%cal Gc6d4,
Gd7b8] Black renews the threat of ...Nxd4 & ...Nc6.} 12. Be2 {White prepares
0-0. Here, it is essential to play} (12. Bb5 {They develop their bishop and
want to take control of the d4-square.} Qh4+ 13. g3 Qh3 $132 {White will have
issues with castling.} 14. Bf1 (14. Qd2 Nb6 $15 {[%cal Gf7f6] Black will play .
..f6 next. White has issues with their king.}) 14... Qh6 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 15. Qf3
(15. Nf5 Qe6 $11) 15... Nc5 16. Qxd5 {This doesn't win a pawn as after} Rd8 17.
Qxc5 Bb6 $17 {[%csl Rd4] the knight on d4 is hanging.}) (12. Bd3 Bb6 $15 {
[%csl Rd4,Re3][%cal Gb6d4]}) 12... Qh4+ 13. g3 Qh6 {[%cal Gd7e5] we want to
take advantage of the vulnerability of the e3-bishop.} 14. Qd2 {defending the
bishop on e3.} (14. Nf5 Qh3 $5 {the more ambitious response.} (14... Qe6 15.
Nd4 Qh6 $11 {leads to a repetition.}) 15. Nd6 (15. Bg4 Qg2 $19) (15. Nd4 $6 Nb6
$17) 15... Nf6 16. exf6 Qe6 $1 {with insane complications to follow up.} 17.
Bc5 (17. fxg7 Rd8 18. Bc5 d4 19. O-O dxc3 {transposes.}) 17... d4 18. O-O dxc3
19. fxg7 Rd8 {White has to be extremely precise here.} 20. Bc4 Qf6 21. Bxf7+ (
21. bxc3 Bb6 22. Bxb6 Rxd6 23. Qa4 Qxc3 $13 {leads to massive complications.})
21... Kxg7 22. Ne8+ {forced.} Kxf7 23. Nxf6 Rxd1 24. Raxd1 Kxf6 25. bxc3 Bf5
$11 {at the end of complications, we end up in a position with two bishops
against a rook.}) (14. Kf2 {can be met with} Bxc3 15. Nxc6 (15. bxc3 Nc5 $11)
15... Qxc6 16. bxc3 Nc5 $11 {[%csl Rd1,Rf2][%cal Gc5e4] Black gets ...Ne4 next.
}) 14... Rd8 $5 {avoiding Nxd5 ideas.} 15. a3 (15. O-O $4 {runs into} Nxd4 16.
Bxd4 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 d4 18. Bxd4 Rxd4 $19 {[%csl Rg1][%cal Ga5b6,Gb6g1] White's
dark-squares are weak.}) 15... Bb6 $1 16. Rd1 (16. Nxd5 $4 Bxd4 17. Bxd4 Nf6
18. exf6 Rxd5 $19 {wins material. For example,} 19. Qe3 Bd7 20. Bc3 Re8 21. Qf2
Bg4 $19) 16... Nc5 $11 {[%cal Gc5e4] with ...Ne4 coming up next. The position
remains extremely complicated.} *

