{[%evp 0,20,20,16,28,28,7,12,27,-2,3,3,23,17,29,4,-11,-1,-11,-33,-16,-21,-5]
In third chapter, we will see a sister line to 4.f3, 4.a3.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {White forces us to give up the bishop.} Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 {
[%cal Gf2f3,Ge2e4] They want to build a 'Saemisch Setup' with f3-e4 next. Here,
I recommend the rare} Ne4 $5 {preventing them from executing their plans.} 6.
Qc2 {the most natural move.} (6. e3 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg1e2]} f5 {improving the
control of the center.} (6... Nxc3 $4 7. Qc2 $18 {White's point.}) 7. Bd3 (7.
Qc2 {transposes.}) (7. Qh5+ $5 {This has been played in a few games, but isn't
impressive.} g6 8. Qh6 Qf6 $5 {the more dynamic option.} (8... Qg5 9. Qxg5 Nxg5
10. f3 b6 $11 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4,Re3] equalises comfortably.}) 9. f3 $5 {a strong
concrete move.} (9. Ne2 Nc6 10. f3 Nd6 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4] White faces issues with
their doubled pawn.}) (9. Bd3 Nc6 10. Ne2 Nd6 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4][%cal Gd6f7,
Ge6e5,Gb7b6,Gc8a6] Black threatens ...b6-Ba6.}) 9... Nd6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal
Gd6c4] focusing on c4.} (9... Nxc3 $4 10. a4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Ga1a3]
the knight's trapped!}) 10. e4 $1 Nf7 (10... fxe4 $4 11. fxe4 Nxe4 12. Nf3 $18
{[%cal Gf1d3,Ge1g1]}) 11. Qe3 d6 12. Bd3 e5 $13 {with a rich strategical
position on the board.}) (7. Ne2 b6 8. f3 Nd6 9. Nf4 Ba6 10. Qa4 O-O 11. Be2 e5
$5 12. dxe5 Nb7 $132) 7... O-O 8. Ne2 (8. Qc2 b6 $1 9. Ne2 (9. Bxe4 $6 fxe4 10.
Qxe4 Nc6 $15 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc8a6,Gc6a5]}) 9... Ba6 $15 {[%csl Rc4][%cal
Gc7c5,Gb8c6,Gc6a5] with a pleasant position for Black. White's pieces are
cramped.}) 8... b6 9. O-O Ba6 {Black always wants to attack the c4-pawn in
these lines.} 10. f3 Nd6 $132) (6. Qd3 $5 {here, instead of the usual ...f5,
we play} d5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6] because after ...b6-Ba6, their queen
will be pinned!} 7. Bf4 {the top choice of engines.} (7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bf4 O-O {
[%csl Rc4] White has the bishop pair but their pawn structure is weak.} 9. f3
$5 (9. Nf3 $6 c5 $15 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gd8a5,Rb8c6,Rc5c4,Rc8f5]}) 9... Nd6 10.
e3 Qh4+ 11. g3 Qe7 $132 {[%csl Rc3,Re3][%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6]}) (7. Nf3 b6 $11 {
[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc8a6,Ga6f1]}) 7... O-O {we want to play ...c5 or ...b6 next.}
8. f3 (8. Nf3 c5 $15 {[%csl Rc3]}) (8. e3 e5 $5 9. Bxe5 Bf5 $132 {[%csl Rc3,
Rc4,Rd3,Rd4][%cal Gf8e8,Gc7c5,Gb8c6] White has issues with their queen on d3/
pawn on c3.}) 8... Nd6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. e3 b6 11. Qc2 Ba6 $11 {[%csl Re3][%cal
Gb8a6,Gc7c5,Gd6c4,Gf8e8] once the bishops are off, the c4-square would be an
accessible square for our knight.}) 6... f5 {This prevents White from playing
f3-e4.} 7. e3 $6 {natural, but dubious} (7. Nf3 b6 8. e3 {transposes.}) (7. g3
$6 b6 8. Bg2 Bb7 {Black doesn't mind trading the light-squared bishops.} 9. Nf3
Nc6 $15 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc6a5]}) (7. Nh3 $5 {[%cal Gf2f3]} O-O (7... b6 $6 8.
f3 Nf6 9. e4) 8. f3 Nf6 9. e3 (9. e4 fxe4 10. fxe4 e5 $5 $132 {[%csl Re1] with
their king in center, we are happy to open up the board.}) 9... c5 10. Bd3 d6
11. O-O Nc6 12. Bd2 Qe7 $132 {[%cal Ge6e5] with a complex strategic battle on
the board. White's central pawns are not mobile at the moment.}) (7. f3 $5 {
the initiation of a tricky complicated line.} Qh4+ 8. g3 Nxg3 9. hxg3 Qxh1 {
we have won the rook but after} 10. Nh3 Qh2 11. Bf4 {our queen is trapped!} d6
{[%cal Gb8c6,Ge6e5]} 12. O-O-O g5 $1 {forcing the knight or bishop to move
away.} 13. Nxg5 (13. Bxg5 Qxg3 $15) 13... Nc6 {[%cal Ge6e5] threatening ...e5.}
14. c5 e5 $132 {White has to play a serious of precise moves in order to
equalise.}) 7... b6 $15 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc8a6] Black is already somewhat
better here!} 8. Bd3 (8. f3 Nd6 $15 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gd6c4] we are glad to
bring the knight towards the c4-pawn.}) (8. Nf3 Ba6 9. Bd3 Nc6 $15 {[%cal
Gc6a5]}) 8... Ba6 9. Ne2 Nc6 10. O-O Na5 $15 {This structure is good for White
if they have f3-e4 included. Here, they seem to be struggling.} *

