{[%evp 0,34,19,34,29,0,-11,-10,25,31,36,23,38,15,22,28,33,11,13,9,42,47,102,36,
17,-4,-24,-79,-82,-82,-88,-69,-88,-81,-81,-81,0] In the fourth chapter, we
will cover the 4.Bd2 0-0 5.e3 system.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bd2 (4.
e3 O-O 5. Bd2 {This is the more common move order for this system. However,
since we don't play 4.e3 0-0 but play 4.Bd2 0-0, this is covered via a
seperate move order.}) 4... O-O 5. e3 {perhaps the most trendy system after 4.
Bd23. White wants to play Bd3-Nf3 next. Here, instead of the usual ...d5, I
recommend the rare} c5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc5d4] undermining their center.} 6. a3
{The critical test.} (6. Nf3 {can be met with the thematic} cxd4 7. exd4 d5 {
[%csl Rc4,Rd4] trying to create an IQP in the center.} 8. c5 {If they play
this, we can play} b6 9. a3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Ne4 11. Rc1 a5 $132 {[%cal Gc8a6]
we'll play ...Ba6 next. Once the bishops are swapped, we'll try to play on the
Queenside.}) (6. Nge2 {can be met with the usual} cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nc6 $11 {
[%csl Rd2][%cal Gd7d5] we'll play ...d5 next. White's bishop on d2 is blocked.}
) (6. Bd3 cxd4 7. exd4 Nc6 8. Nf3 d5 {hoping to create an IQP. If they play c5,
we'll play ...b6 next.}) (6. d5 {the combination of Bd2 & d5 isn't great.} exd5
7. Nxd5 (7. cxd5 d6 8. Nge2 Nbd7 $11 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rd7b6] we'll play ...Nb6
next to attack the d5-pawn.}) 7... Bxd2+ 8. Qxd2 Nxd5 9. cxd5 d6 $132 {[%cal
Gb8d7,Ga7a6] without a couple of minor pieces, Black's pieces are cramped.}) (
6. dxc5 Bxc5 7. Nf3 d5 $11 {[%csl Rd2] White's bishop on d2 is misplaceds.
Because of this, we don't mind accepting the IQP.}) 6... Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 {
[%csl Rc3][%cal Ge4c3] we want to spoil their pawn structure.} 8. Ne2 {trying
to maintain their pawn structure.} (8. Rc1 {same plan, White wants to
maintains their pawn structure.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge4c3]} 9. Nf3 (9. Bd3 Nxc3
10. Rxc3 Bb7 11. Nf3 {transposes.}) 9... Bb7 10. Bd3 (10. Be2 d6 11. O-O Nxc3
$1 {important!} (11... Nd7 12. Be1 {gives White the chance to retain the
bishop pair.}) 12. Rxc3 Qe7 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge6e5] with two minor pieces off
the board, Black keeps an easier game. You want to play ...Nd7 & ...e5 next.})
10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 {transposes.} f5 {increasing the control of the center.}
12. O-O d6 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd8e7,Ge6e5,Yd8f6] Black will want to play ...e5
down the line. Optically, Black keeps an easier game due to the expansion
possibilities.}) (8. Qc2 {allows us to liqiuidate comfortably.} Nxc3 9. Qxc3
cxd4 10. exd4 b6 {whenever we trade pieces in this structure, we keep an
easier game. They'll face problems with their central pawns.} 11. Nf3 Bb7 12.
Be2 Nc6 13. O-O d6 14. b4 Rc8 $11 {[%csl Gb7,Rc4,Rd4,Gd8,Rf3][%cal Gd8f6,Yc6e7,
Ye7f5]}) 8... b6 9. d5 {[%cal Gd1d3] the critical test. White gains space and
threatens Qd3.} (9. f3 {has been played by a couple of strong players. However,
after} Nxc3 10. Nxc3 cxd4 11. Qxd4 Nc6 12. Qf4 Ba6 $1 $11 {[%cal Ga8c8,Yc6e7,
Yd7d5] Black equalises comfortably. We'll target the c4-pawn.}) (9. Qc2 Nxc3
10. Nxc3 (10. Qxc3 Bb7 $11) 10... cxd4 11. exd4 Nc6 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4][%cal Gc8a6,
Ga8c8,Gd7d5] also equalises comfortably.}) 9... Ba6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb6b5]
the most ambitiouss response by Black. We target the c4-pawn.} 10. Qd3 {
initiating a tactical sequence.} (10. b3 b5 {undermining their center.} 11. Qc2
$5 (11. Qd3 {can be met with} Nxc3 12. Nxc3 bxc4 13. bxc4 exd5 14. Qxd5 (14.
Nxd5 Nc6 15. Be2 (15. Qd2 Ne7 $11 {[%csl Rc4,Re1][%cal Ge7d5,Gd8a5,Ga5a4] once
we play ...Qa5+, we remain on the better end of equality.}) 15... Qa5+ 16. Qd2
Rab8 $11 {Black's pieces are optimally placed.}) 14... Qa5 15. Qd2 Nc6 16. Be2
Rab8 {Black retains more active pieces.} (16... Ne5 17. Nb5 $14) 17. O-O (17.
Nb5 d5 $15 {[%csl Rb5,Rc4] White has issues maintaining their knight.}) 17...
Ne5 $11 {with an equal position. White needs to be careful here. If anyone can
press here, it's Black.}) 11... exd5 12. cxd5 Nxc3 13. Nxc3 {the most played
move.} (13. Qxc3 {[%csl Rd5] looks a bit awkward.} d6 14. Ng3 Nd7 15. Be2 Nf6
$11 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf8e8,Ge8e5,Ga8b8,Gd8b6,Gb5b4] without two minor pieces
on the board, Black faces no problems with space. We'll play ...Re8 & ...Rb8
next.}) 13... b4 {forcing liquidation!} 14. Ne4 (14. Bxa6 Nxa6 15. Na4 bxa3 $11
) 14... Bxf1 15. Kxf1 d6 16. axb4 cxb4 $11 {[%cal Ga7a5,Yf7f5,Yb8d7,Yd7c5]
with a comfortable equality for Black.}) (10. Rc1 {can be met with} Bxc4 {
taking on the challenge!} 11. Bxg7 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Kxg7 13. Qg4+ Qg5 14. Qxe4
Qxd5 15. Qxd5 exd5 16. Rd1 d4 17. exd4 Re8+ 18. Kd2 cxd4 $11 {with an easier
endgame for Black thanks to the extra pawn.}) (10. f3 {runs into a tactical
shot.} Nxc3 11. Nxc3 Bxc4 $1 12. Bxc4 Qh4+ 13. g3 Qxc4 $11 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c7]
It is White who needs to be precise in order to equalise here. Remember to
play ...Na6-c7 here.}) 10... exd5 11. Qxd5 Qe7 $1 {important! 12.Qxa8 Nc6 is
the tactical justification.} 12. b3 {runs into a thematic blow.} (12. Be5 $6 {
can be met with} Bb7 13. Qxb7 Qxe5 $15 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Ge5b2] White is
already worse.} 14. Qxa8 $4 {This loses after} Nc6 15. Qb7 Qxb2 16. Rd1 Qxa3) (
12. g3 {can be met with} Nc6 13. Bg2 Nxc3 14. Nxc3 Na5 $15 {[%csl Rc4] White's
c4 pawn continues to haunt them.}) (12. Rd1 Nc6 {This is already uncomfortable
for White.} 13. b3 (13. Qxd7 $6 Qh4 14. g3 Qh5 $15 {[%csl Gc6,Rd7,Re1,Ge4]
[%cal Gh5f3,Re4c3,Re2c3,Rc6e5,Re5f3] White faces tactical issues.}) 13... Rfe8
{[%csl Rf2][%cal Ge4f2]} 14. Bb2 Nxf2 15. Kxf2 Qxe3+ 16. Ke1 Qxb3 $44 {White
has to be precise in order to equalise here.}) (12. Rc1 {[%cal Rc1c3,Re2g3]
preparing Ng3.} Nc6 13. Ng3 (13. f3 Nxc3 14. Rxc3 Qh4+ {[%csl Rf3][%cal Ga8e8,
Rg2g3,Rh4f6] inducing more weaknesses in their camp.}) 13... Nxc3 14. Rxc3 Rad8
15. Be2 Na5 $11 {[%cal Ga6b7] threatening ...Bb7. The position remains
balanced.}) 12... Re8 {[%cal Ge4f2]} 13. Bb2 Nxf2 $1 {the point behind ...Re8.}
14. Kxf2 Qxe3+ 15. Ke1 Qxb3 16. Qd2 Bxc4 17. Kf2 d5 $132 {Black's compensation
is self-evident.} *

