{[%evp 0,22,16,16,28,14,14,7,23,23,32,26,26,35,36,23,12,16,41,28,32,39,39,45,
51] In the fifth chapter, we will cover the 4.e3 variation in the Nimzo.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 {as usual, I offer a creative suggestion with}
Nc6 {[%cal Ge6e5] the idea is to meet the most natural 5.Bd3 with ...e5 on the
next move.} 5. Bd3 {The most natural and widely played response. White
prepares Nge2-0-0.} (5. Bd2 {This can be played by players who play the e3-Bd2
system. This is not widely played, but the computer believes to be White's
best setup against 4...Nc6.} O-O 6. Bd3 {the most widely played move.} (6. Qc2
{computer's top choice. This is far from obvious though.} e5 7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. a3
Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Re8 10. Nf3 d6 11. Be2 Qe7 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Re5f3,Rf6e4] If
they play Nxe5, we'll play ...b6 & ...Bb7 next. Otherwise, Black wants to play
...Nxf3-Ne4-Bf5.}) (6. Nf3 {this natural move doesn't pose any problems. After}
Bxc3 7. Bxc3 Ne4 8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 d6 $11 {[%cal Gd8e7,Ge6e5,Ga7a5,Gb7b6]
followed by ...a5-b6- ...Qe7 & ...e5, Black keeps a comfortable position.})
6... e5 {sticking to the setup.} 7. d5 Ne7 8. Nge2 a5 9. a3 (9. O-O d6 $132 {
[%cal Gb4c5,Ge7g6,Gc7c6] Black will play ...Ng6-c6 next to challenge White's
center. The position remains strategically rich. If they play a3, we'll play ..
.Bc5.}) 9... Bc5 10. Na4 {engine's choice.} Ba7 11. Bxa5 {White's point.} (11.
O-O d6 {leads to a comfortable game for Black.}) 11... Bxe3 12. d6 Rxa5 {
sacrificing a piece!} 13. dxe7 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 Qxe7 15. Nac3 e4 {[%csl Rf2] the
engine is initally optimistic about White's chances but the enthuasiasm fades
down as we go deep. From a practical perspective, this position is unclear.
Black threatens ...Ng4-Ne3 or ...Rf5+. Their king is super exposed.}) (5. Nf3 {
can be met with the thematic} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d6 {[%cal Gf2f3,Re3e4] White is
usually better in these lines if they are able to play f3-e4. Without that,
Black doesn't find this position to be challenging.} 7. Bd3 e5 8. e4 O-O 9. O-O
Bg4 {[%csl Rd4] asking them to play d5 so that the c5-square is weakened.} 10.
Be3 Re8 11. h3 (11. Rb1 b6 $11 {[%cal Gc6e7,Ge7g6,Rd4d5]}) 11... Bh5 12. d5 {
White had to release the tension sooner or later.} Ne7 13. a4 c6 $13 {[%csl
Rc3,Rc4,Rd5][%cal Gf6d7,Gh5g6] with a complex strategic middlegame on the
board.}) (5. Qc2 O-O 6. Nf3 {White claims to have maintained their pawn
structure.} (6. Bd2 {transposes.}) (6. Bd3 e5 {this is a better version of the
...e5 lines for Black.} 7. d5 {runs into} (7. Nge2 Re8 8. O-O Bxc3 9. Qxc3 d5
$132 {Black keeps more active pieces after the pawn trades in the center.})
7... e4 $1 8. Bxe4 (8. Be2 Ne5 $11) 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nxe4 10. Qxe4 Na5 $15 {
[%csl Rc4] they don't have a light-squared bishop anymore!}) 6... d6 {[%cal
Ge6e5] preparing the usual ...e5.} 7. Bd3 (7. Bd2 e5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 $132 {
[%cal Gd8e7,Gb7b6] leads to the usual dynamic positions. We'll play ...Qe7 & ..
b6 next. If they don't capture on e5, Black keeps the option of playing ...Bg4.
}) 7... e5 8. O-O Bxc3 {spoiling their structure.} 9. bxc3 Re8 10. Nd2 exd4 11.
exd4 h6 $13 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6] we'll play ...b6-Ba6 next. The
position remains rich strategically.}) (5. a3 $6 {allows us to execute our
plans.} Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 b6 $15 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc8a6] we have a tempo up version of
the Saemisch. White has played e3 unnecessarily. They want f3-e4 in this
system.}) (5. Nge2 {If their bishop is not on d3, the plan with ...e5 doesn't
make a lot of sense.} d5 {the only time we go for ...d5.} 6. a3 (6. Ng3 {
can be met with} h5 $1 7. h4 Bd6 $15 {[%csl Rg3]}) (6. cxd5 {the inclusion of
the pawn trade helps Black.} exd5 {[%cal Gc8f5] the bishop can come out to f5.
Something like} 7. g3 {can be met with} Bf5 8. Bg2 Qd7 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gh7h5,
Gh5h4] with a potential attack down the Kingside!}) 6... Bd6 {provoking c5.} 7.
c5 (7. cxd5 exd5 8. g3 {can be met with} Ne7 9. Bg2 O-O 10. Nb5 Bf5 $11 {
[%csl Rc1][%cal Ge7g6] Black's pieces are optimally placed. White faces
problems with their c1-bishop.}) (7. Ng3 {can be met with the usual} h5 8. c5
h4 9. Nge2 Be7 $132 {[%cal Ge6e5,Rb7b6] we'll play ...e5 or ...b6 next.}) 7...
Be7 {[%cal Ge6e5] we can now play ...e5 as the d5-pawn isn't attacked anymore.}
8. b4 {runs into the thematic} (8. Nf4 $5 a5 $1 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gc6b8,Gc7c6,Gb8d7,
Re6e5,Rb7b6] avoiding b4. Black will play ...0-0-Nb8-c6-Nbd7 next. We can then
think of playing ...b6 & ...e5.}) 8... e5 9. Bb2 {the easiest way to deal with
this is to play} (9. g3 {is met with the thematic} h5 $5 10. b5 (10. h4 Bg4 $15
{[%csl Rf3,Rg2,Rh3][%cal Ge5e4]}) 10... exd4 11. exd4 Na5 $132 {[%csl Rc4]
[%cal Gh5h4]}) 9... exd4 10. exd4 O-O 11. g3 Re8 12. Bg2 Bf8 {[%cal Gg7g6,
Gc6e7,Gc7c6] followed by ...g6-Bg7-Ne7-c6.}) 5... e5 {This is why we played ...
Nc6!} 6. Nge2 (6. d5 e4 7. Be2 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Na5 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4][%cal
Gb7b6,Gc8a6] White's pawn structure is spoilt.}) 6... Bxc3+ {asking them to
spoil their structure.} 7. bxc3 {most logical.} (7. Nxc3 {is also possible.}
exd4 8. exd4 d5 {striking back in the center.} (8... Nxd4 9. O-O O-O 10. Bg5
$16 {leads to some problems on the h4-d8 diagonal.}) 9. Bg5 dxc4 10. Bxc4 O-O
$11 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gh7h6] White has problems with their IQP.}) 7... e4 {
fixing their structure.} 8. Bb1 (8. Bc2 Na5 9. Ng3 Nxc4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4
{transposes.}) 8... Na5 9. Ng3 Nxc4 10. Nxe4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 d5 $11 {[%csl Rc1]
we have fixed their structure. Black will play ...Be6 & ...0-0 next.} *

