{[%evp 0,22,16,16,28,7,6,6,20,17,16,16,29,28,27,20,12,22,21,21,31,28,28,-26,-8]
In the sixth chapter, we will cover 4.Nf3 against the Nimzo.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4
e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 {White cannot play f3-e4 anymore.} Bxc3+ {we continue to
spoil their pawn structure.} 5. bxc3 d6 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4][%cal Ge6e5] We want to
play ...e5 next. White cannot play f3-e4 next while spoiling their pawn
structure.} 6. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4] White prepares e4.} (6. g4 $5 {some strong
players like Wojtaszek and Bluebaum has tried it. We cannot play ...Nxg4 due
to Rg1.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] we are going for ...Bb7-Qe7-Nfd7-Nc6-e5 next.} 7. g5
Nfd7 8. h4 Bb7 9. h5 Qe7 10. h6 g6 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge8c8] we'll play ...Nc6
& ...0-0-0 next.}) (6. Bg5 {One of the two major moves.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gh7h6,
Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Ge6e5] our main plan is to play ...b6 & ...e5 next.} 7. e3 {
the most natural move.} (7. Qc2 {White prepares e4.} h6 8. Bh4 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,
Gg7g5,Gf6h5] once the queen is on c2, ...g5-Nh5 becomes a reasonable option.}
9. e4 Bb7 10. Bd3 g5 $132) 7... b6 8. Nd2 (8. Bd3 Bb7 $15 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gg7g5,
Gf6e4] we'll play ...h6-g5-Ne4.}) 8... h6 9. Bh4 e5 10. Bd3 Bb7 {[%cal Gh6h5,
Gg7g5] we'll play ...g5-h5 or ...Qe7 & ...0-0-0 next.} 11. O-O g5 12. Bg3 h5
$132) (6. e3 Nc6 {transposes to the 4.e3 Nc6!? variation.}) (6. g3 $6 {with
the c4-pawn being weak, this is never good.} b6 7. Bg2 Bb7 8. O-O O-O $11 {
[%cal Gb8c6,Gc6a5] we'll play ...Nc6-Na5 next. The c4-pawn is vulnerable.}) (6.
Nd2 {can be met with the usual} e5 7. e4 Nc6 8. Bb2 Ne7 $132 {[%cal Ge7g6,
Gb7b6] we'll play ...Ng6 & ...0-0 next. White's pawn structure is spoiled.}) (
6. a4 $5 {this was played by Mamedyarov twice.} Nc6 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 7. a5 {
Mamed's point. However, after} O-O 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 e5 $132 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gg7g5,
Gc8f5] Black still retains counterplay. We'll play ...Qe7-g5-Bf5 next.}) 6...
O-O {again, White can choose from two moves.} 7. e4 {can be met with} (7. Bg5
b6 8. e4 (8. Nd2 {can be met with} Bb7 9. e4 $5 h6 10. Bh4 e5 $132 {[%cal
Gf8e8,Gb8d7] with ...Re8-Nbd7-Nf8 coming in next. if they play f3, Bf2, ...
Nh5-f4 is up on the cards.}) (8. e3 Bb7 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. O-O {here, Black can
expand on the Kingside} h6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Ne4 {[%cal Gf7f5]}) 8... e5 $5 {
as usual, we meet e4 with ...e5.} 9. Bd3 (9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Nxe5 {this is too
weak. After} Qe7 11. f4 Na6 {[%csl Re4][%cal Ga6c5,Gc5e4] White's pawns can be
exploited.} 12. Be2 Nc5 13. Bf3 Qe6 14. O-O Bb7 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4,Re4] we
threaten ...Nxe4. We keep a much better pawn structure.}) 9... h6 10. Bh4 (10.
Be3 Re8 $132 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gb8c6] we'll play ...Nc6 next.}) 10... Re8 11. O-O
Nbd7 $132 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gc8b7,Yg7g5,Rd7f8,Rf7f6,Rf8g6] maintaining the pressure.
Black can play ...g5 or ...Nf8-Ng6 or ...Bb7 next.}) 7... e5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal
Ge5d4] the usual response against e4.} 8. Bd3 (8. Be2 {can be met with} Re8 {
provoking d5.} 9. d5 Nbd7 10. Be3 Nc5 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6,Ga7a5] the knight on c5
seems strong. We'll play ...b6-a5 next.}) 8... Nc6 {provoking d4.} 9. O-O (9.
d5 Ne7 $15 {[%cal Gf6d7] we'll play ...Nd7-Nc5 next.}) (9. h3 {runs into} exd4
10. cxd4 Nb4 $15 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb4d3,Gf8e8,Ge8e4]}) 9... exd4 10. cxd4 Bg4
11. d5 Nb4 $11 {we'll grab the bishop on d3.} *

