{[%evp 0,38,14,16,28,6,6,28,23,-8,-1,-9,-9,6,-9,-11,-11,-33,-33,-53,-43,-44,
-11,-11,6,0,-2,-2,14,14,8,8,-6,-10,0,0,-1,-13,-6,-16,4] In the seventh chapter,
we cover the 4.g3 variation in the Nimzo.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. g3
{a hybrid of the Nimzo Indian & the Catalan. White will play Bg2 & Nf3 sooner
or later.} O-O 5. Bg2 d5 6. Nf3 dxc4 7. O-O Nc6 {all of this is established
theory. Here's the first branching point.} 8. Qa4 {White wants to Ne5/Qb5 next.
} (8. Re1 {against this, I recommend the rare} h6 $1 {stopping all Bg5 ideas,
which were a problem in Rb8 lines} (8... Rb8 {this is the most played move.
After} 9. a3 Bxc3 10. bxc3 b5 11. Bg5 {White can apply some practical pressure
here.}) 9. a3 (9. e4 {can be met with} Rb8 {preparing ...b5.} 10. e5 (10. a3
Bxc3 11. bxc3 {transposes.}) 10... Nd5 11. Bd2 b5 12. Ne4 Nce7 $17 {White
doesn't have sufficient compensation for the missing pawn.}) 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3
Rb8 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 11. e4 {the critical test. Against 11...b5, White wants to
play g4.} (11. Nd2 {can be met with} Nd5 12. Nxc4 Nxc3 13. Qb3 Nd5 $11 {
[%cal Gb7b5] followed by ...b5 or ...b6 next. Black keeps easy play.}) 11...
Re8 $1 {[%cal Ge6e5] keeping an eye out for e5. White basically has one setup
here, Bf4-Qe2-Rad1} (11... b5 12. g4 $5 $132 {[%cal Gh2h4]}) 12. Bf4 ({moves
like} 12. g4 {allow} e5 $15) (12. a4 e5 $1 {also favours Black.}) (12. Qe2 b5
13. Bf4 Bb7 {transposes.}) 12... b5 13. Qe2 Bb7 14. Rad1 a6 {we'll reach this
position somehow. White wants to push g4, but for that, h4-Nh2 needs to happen.
We'll meet Nh2 with e5, and therefore put our Queen on e7.} 15. h4 (15. a4 Nd7
$1 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 16. h4 e5 17. axb5 axb5 18. dxe5 Qe7 $11 {with a comfortable
position for Black. White needs to be precise in order to equalise.}) 15... Qe7
16. a4 (16. Nh2 e5 $17 {is our point.}) 16... Nd7 {sacrificing a pawn to
prepare ...e5.} 17. Bxc7 Rbc8 18. Bf4 e5 $13 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5,Gc4][%cal Ge5d4] I
find the position to be slightly easier to play as Black.}) (8. a3 {the most
widely played move. However, I find this to be a bit weaker than the text.} Be7
9. e4 a6 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gb7b5,Ga5b3,Gc8b7,Gc7c5] this is just good for black.
White doesn't have sufficient compensation.} 10. Be3 {covering the c5-break 
(after ...Na5).} (10. Bf4 b5 11. Qe2 Na5 12. Rad1 Bb7 $15 {[%cal Ga5b3,Gc7c5]
we'll play ...Nb3 & ...c5 next.}) (10. h4 $5 Na5 $1 $17 {[%csl Rc1][%cal Ga5b3]
is quite strong.}) 10... b5 11. Qe2 (11. h4 {[%csl Rg4] runs into} Ng4 (11...
Rb8 {also makes a lot of sense.}) 12. Bf4 e5 $1 13. dxe5 h6 $1 $11 {[%cal
Gc8e6,Re7c5,Yd8b8,Ya6a5] preparing ...Be6-Bc5. Black retains a comfortable
game without giving any counterplay.}) 11... Bb7 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gc7c5] preparing
...Na5-c5.} 12. Rad1 Na5 13. d5 (13. Ne5 {the most widely played move.} Nb3 14.
f4 Qe8 $1 {[%cal Gc7c5] preparing ...c5.} (14... Nd7 15. f5 $5) 15. g4 (15. f5
c5 $17) 15... Nd7 16. f5 c5 $17 {Black retains a massive advantage thanks to
the generated play in the center.}) 13... exd5 14. e5 Ne8 15. e6 {This was
played by Pragg against Gukesh. Here, after} fxe6 16. Nd4 Qd6 17. Bf4 Rxf4 18.
gxf4 Nf6 19. Nxe6 c6 $17 {[%csl Re6,Rf4][%cal Ga8e8,Re7f8,Rb7c8,Ya5b3,Yd5d4]
Black retains a massive advantage thanks to their pawns. We'll play ...
Rae8-Bc8 and look to roll the pawns.}) (8. Bg5 {giving up the bishop doesn't
help White.} h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. e3 Bxc3 $1 11. bxc3 Rb8 $11 {[%cal Gb7b5,
Gc6a5,Yc8a6] we'll play ...b5 or ...Na5-b6 next (if they play Nd2).}) (8. Rb1 {
played by a few theoreticians.} h6 {sticking to the usual plan.} 9. a3 Be7 10.
e4 a6 $15 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc6a5] the rook on b1 doesn't help White. They have
basically wasted a tempo.}) 8... Nd5 {forcing Qc2.} 9. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4] White
threatens e4.} (9. Bd2 Nb6 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gc6d4]}) 9... Be7 {vacating
the b4-square for the knight. Black anticipates e4.} 10. Rd1 (10. e4 {runs into
} Ndb4 11. Qe2 Nxd4 $17) 10... a5 $5 $146 {A strong novelty. We are looking to
gain space with b5 at some point. The alternate idea is to play a4-a3. If
white plays Na4, we get b5 and consolidate the pawn on c4.} 11. e4 {the
principled response. White gains space.} (11. Ne4 {can be met with} Ncb4 12.
Qb1 (12. Qxc4 b5 13. Qxb5 Ba6 $15 {[%csl Re2][%cal Ga6e2] Black takes over.})
12... f5 $1 13. Nc3 Bf6 $15 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gd5c3,Gb4d5]}) (11. a3 a4 $1 {our
point!} 12. Nxa4 b5 13. Nc3 Ncb4 $1 {[%csl Ra1][%cal Ga8a1] Black makes full
use of the open a-file!} 14. Qb1 {the most logical. However, after} (14. Qd2
Nxc3 15. Qxc3 (15. bxc3 Nd5 $15 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Re2e4,Rd5b6,Rb6a4,Gc7c5]
their pawn structure is spoiled.}) 15... Nd5 16. Qc2 {here, we can repeat with
...Nb4 or play} Bb7 $11) 14... Nxc3 15. bxc3 Nd5 16. Bd2 Bd7 {[%csl Ra3] Black
is on top..}) (11. h4 a4 $1 {the usual plan.} 12. e3 (12. Nxa4 Ncb4 $19) 12...
Ncb4 $15 {[%cal Gb7b5]} 13. Qe2 b5 14. Nxb5 Ba6 15. Nc3 a3 $1 $15 {Black
generates a lot of play on the Queenside.}) (11. e3 {can be met with} b5 12.
Nxb5 Ncb4 13. Qe2 Ba6 14. Nc3 Nd3 $11 {[%cal Ge6d5,Ga5a4,Rc3d5] with a
comfortable equality. Optically, our position looks a bit more appealing.})
11... Ncb4 12. Qb1 (12. Qd2 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd3 $15 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6] White
doesn't have sufficient compensation.}) 12... Nxc3 13. bxc3 Nd3 {we want to
play ...c5 or ...b6-Ba6 next.} 14. Qb5 $1 {going for the c4-pawn.} (14. Be3 {
can be met with} b6 $15 {[%cal Gc8a6,Yb6b5,Yc7c5] preparing ...Ba6-c5 or ...b5.
Black remains up due to the extra pawn.}) 14... b6 15. Qxc4 Ba6 16. Qc6 $5 {
stopping ...c5.} (16. Qb3 {can be met with} c5 17. Be3 c4 18. Qc2 b5 $132 {
[%cal Gf7f5,Rb5b4] we'll play ...b4 or ...f5 next.}) 16... Qd6 $1 {perhaps the
cleanest solution.} 17. Qxd6 Bxd6 18. a4 (18. Be3 {is weak because after} Nb2
19. Rdb1 Nc4 {[%cal Gc4e3,Ga8b8,Gc7c5] Black keeps some practical pressure.})
18... Nxc1 19. Raxc1 b5 $5 $11 {[%csl Ga5] comp claims this is equal but due
to the possibility of creating an outside passed pawn, I think Black keeps
chances in the endgame.} *

