{[%evp 0,30,16,19,22,6,14,14,29,-7,5,-26,-25,-31,-25,-29,9,0,30,12,17,13,31,44,
28,23,36,19,20,22,72,10,10] In the final chapter, we'll cover the miscallenous
options for White on the 4th move.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 (4.
Bd2 O-O 5. a3 (5. Nf3 {White intentionally delays playing e3. This avoids the .
..c5 line.} b6 {waiting for them to commit to a plan.} 6. e3 (6. g3 {can be
met with} Ba6 $5 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ga6c4] they have problems with the c4-pawn.
If they play b3, we can play ...d5.}) 6... c5 {now that they have played e3,
we can play ...c5.} 7. a3 (7. Bd3 {can be met with} d5 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 dxc4
10. Bxc4 Ne4 $11 {[%cal Ge4c3,Gc8b7,Gb8d7] with a very comfortable game for
Black.}) 7... Bxc3 8. Bxc3 Ne4 {the usual response against a3.} 9. Qc2 Nxc3 10.
Qxc3 d6 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gb8d7,Ge6e5] we'll play ...Bb7-Nbd7-Qe7-e5 next.}) (5.
e3 c5 {transposes to 4.e3 0-0 5.Bd2 lines.}) 5... Bxc3 6. Bxc3 Ne4 {This is
our usual response to Bd2-a3 lines.} 7. Qc2 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gc2e4] forcing us
to take on c3.} (7. Rc1 {can be met with} d6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge6e5] preparing ...
Nd7-e5.} 8. Nf3 Nd7 9. g3 e5 10. Bg2 (10. dxe5 Nxc3 11. Rxc3 dxe5 $11 {[%cal
Gc7c6,Gd8e7,Ga7a5] Black is able to build some pressure on the dark-squares
here.}) 10... Nxc3 11. Rxc3 e4 12. Nd2 f5) 7... Nxc3 8. Qxc3 b6 9. Nf3 Bb7 10.
g3 {here, ...d6-Nd7 remains a decent option. What we recommend is the more
ambitious} (10. e3 {can be met with} Bxf3 11. gxf3 Qh4 $5 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gd7d5,
Ye6e5] creating imbalances. White doesn't have a safe spot for their king at
the moment.}) 10... c5 11. Bg2 cxd4 12. Qxd4 Nc6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c4]
looking to generate play on the c-file.} 13. Qf4 Rc8 14. O-O Na5 15. Nd2 Qc7
$11 {the resulting endgames are more comfortable for Black due to the weak
c4-pawn.}) (4. Qb3 c5 {If the queen moves to b3/a4, ...c5 becomes an automatic
choice.} 5. dxc5 {the most widely played move.} (5. e3 Nc6 6. Nf3 {transposes.}
) (5. Nf3 Nc6 6. e3 cxd4 7. exd4 d5 {Black manages to create an IQP.}) 5... Nc6
6. Nf3 (6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 {can be met with} g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 {[%csl Rc3][%cal
Ge4c5,Yb4c3] threatening to spoil their structure.. A possible line is} 9. e3
Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Nxc5 11. Qc2 d6 {Black will build up a pawn fortress on the
dark squares.} 12. Nf3 e5 13. h4 Rf8 14. O-O-O Qf6 $15 {[%csl Rg3] we'll
castle long. Their bishop on g3 is dead, while their structure remains spoilt.}
) 6... Ne4 {looking to spoil their structure.} 7. Bd2 {White gives up their
bishop.} Nxd2 8. Nxd2 Bxc5 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Ge8g8] with a comfortable
equality. We'll play ...0-0-b6-Bb7 next.}) (4. Bf4 {runs into the thematic} c5
5. e3 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 {[%csl Re4][%cal Gb8c6,Rf6e4] we'll either play ...Ne4
or create an IQP.}) (4. g4 {is a bit too much. The simplest response is} d5 5.
a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4,Rd4,Rg4] their structure is spoilt for
no reason.}) (4. Qa4 {is met with the thematic} c5 5. dxc5 (5. Nf3 Nc6 6. e3
cxd4 7. exd4 d5 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4] IQP}) 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Na6 7. Qa3 Qc7 $15 {
Black will regain the pawn and keep a better structure.}) 4... c5 {It is
important to delay ...h6 here!} 5. d5 {the critical move.} (5. e3 Qa5 $17 {
[%csl Rg5][%cal Gf6e4]}) (5. Nf3 $5 {If they play Nf3, we can play ...h6.} h6
6. Bh4 g5 7. Bg3 g4 {the point!} 8. Ne5 Ne4 $17 {[%csl Rc3,Rd4][%cal Gb4c3,
Gc5d4,Gd8a5] White will have a hard time defending threats against c3 & d4
simultaneously.}) (5. dxc5 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Qa5 {we end up having a better
structure.}) 5... d6 {[%csl Gb4] going for a much better version of the Benoni.
} 6. e3 (6. f3 $6 O-O 7. e4 b5 {[%csl Re1,Rf1,Rg1] this is too much for White
to handle.} 8. dxe6 Bxe6 9. cxb5 h6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bf2 d5 $15 {Black's
initative flows through the center.}) (6. Nf3 {whenever they play Nf3, we can
play ...h6.} h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 $15 {[%cal Gf7f5] we'll play ...f5 or
spoil their structure. Black doesn't have to worry about getting hit with f3
here.}) 6... Bxc3+ $5 {spoiling their structure.} 7. bxc3 e5 {A closed
position and a spoilt pawn structure for White. What more can Black ask for?}
8. Qc2 (8. f3 {can be met with} h6 9. Bh4 e4 $15 {[%csl Re3,Rf3] If they play
f4, we'll play ...g5-Qe7.}) (8. Bd3 {can be met with} h6 $5 9. Bh4 e4 $1 {
winning a tempo.} 10. Bc2 (10. Bxe4 $4 g5 $19 {was the point.}) 10... g5 11.
Bg3 Qe7 {[%cal Ge8d8,Gd8c7,Gb8d7] we'll play ...Nd7 & swing the king over to
c7.} 12. h4 Rg8 13. hxg5 hxg5 14. Ne2 Nbd7 15. Qb1 Kd8 $15 {[%cal Gd8c7,Yb7b6,
Yc8a6,Rd7b6] after ...Kc7, our king will be safe. We can then think of playing
on the Queenside with ...b6-Ba6 or ...Nb6.}) (8. Nf3 h6 {the usual response
against Nf3.} 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Qe7 11. Nd2 Bf5 {[%cal Gh8g8,Gb8d7,Ge8d8,Gd8c7]
preparing ...Nd7-Kd8-Kc7.} 12. h4 Rg8 13. hxg5 hxg5 14. Qb3 {White discourages
...Nbd7.} Qc7 $15 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge8c8] renewing the threat of ...Nbd7. We may
even castle long this time.}) 8... h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Qe7 11. Nf3 {here, we
play} e4 12. Nd2 Bf5 {preparing ...Nbd7 & ...0-0-0.} 13. Rb1 {trying to
discourage ...Nbd7. If they haven't played h4, we can also play} (13. h4 O-O
$15 {with the queen facing away from the Kingside, this is quite safe. Black
can play ...Kg7 next.}) 13... O-O $1 14. Be2 Bg6 15. h4 b6 $17 {[%cal Gb8d7]
the closed positions favour Black due to the pawn structure and presence of
knights.} *

